{{Politics of Egypt}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Egypt]] on 19 March 2011,<ref>{{cite web|last=Zayan |first=Jailan |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gLzgMRN5vmANBUJBTJJqvayXqWEg?docId=CNG.0f69b85278e292f4cec1b79291e88739.671 |title=AFP: New Egypt PM addresses crowds in Tahrir Square |publisher=Google.com |date=2011-03-04 |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> following the [[Egyptian Revolution of 2011]]. The 1971 [[Constitution of Egypt|constitution]] was suspended by the [[Supreme Council of the Armed Forces]] on 13 February, two days after the resignation of [[Hosni Mubarak]]. The Council has organized a [[Egypt Constitutional Review Committee of 2011|committee of jurists]] to draft amendments to pave the way for new elections. The referendum was held in March, with parliamentary and then presidential elections planned afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gyvIy92hyHZzDwY3N_T-NwAdrdeQ?docId=CNG.64b40623ef755670eb1e7e108c8d3448.801 |title=Egypt cyber activists say they met military rulers |publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/02/27/us-egypt-referendum-idUSTRE71Q11620110227 |title=Egypt to call March referendum this week: lawyer |publisher=Reuters |date= |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref>
